nguages\n| blank1_info_sec1       = {{PH wikidata|language}}\n| blank2_name_sec1       = Sister localities\n| blank2_info_sec1       = \n| blank3_name_sec1       = \n| blank3_info_sec1       = \n| blank4_name_sec1       = \n| blank4_info_sec1       = \n| blank5_name_sec1       = \n| blank5_info_sec1       = \n| blank6_name_sec1       = \n| blank6_info_sec1       = \n| blank7_name_sec1       = \n| blank7_info_sec1       = \n| blank1_name_sec2       = Major religions\n| blank1_info_sec2       = \n| blank2_name_sec2       = Feast date\n| blank2_info_sec2       = \n| blank3_name_sec2       = Catholic diocese\n| blank3_info_sec2       =\n| blank4_name_sec2       = Patron saint \n| blank4_info_sec2       = {{PH wikidata|patron_saint}}\n| blank5_name_sec2       = \n| blank5_info_sec2       = \n| blank6_name_sec2       = \n| blank6_info_sec2       = \n| blank7_name_sec2       = \n| blank7_info_sec2       =\n| short_description      =\n| footnotes              =\n}}\n\n'''{{PH wikidata|name}}''', officially the '''{{PH wikidata|official_name}}''' ({{IPA-tl|h\u0254\u031d\u027ed\u0250n|}}),  is a {{PH wikidata|income_class_ordinal}} [[{{PH wikidata|settlement_text}} of the Philippines|{{PH wikidata|settlement_text}}]] and capital of the [[Philippine Province|province]] of {{PH wikidata|province}}, {{PH wikidata|country}}. According to the {{PH wikidata|population_as_of}}, it has a population of {{PH wikidata|population_total}} people, making it the second largest settlement in the province.{{PH census|current}}\n\nWith a [[wharf]] closest to [[Iloilo City]] and a central location, Jordan is also the commercial center of the island.<ref name=Jordan>{{cite web|title=Jordan|url=http://guimaras.gov.ph/homepage/jordan/|publisher=Province of Guimaras|accessdate=31 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nJordan is bounded by the three municipalities of the province, [[Buenavista, Guimaras|Buenavista]] to the north, [[San Lorenzo, Guimaras|San Lorenzo]] to the east, and [[Sibunag, Guimaras|Sibunag]] to the south. Before founding of the five towns, the whole island of Guimaras was called \"Himal-us\".  Across the [[Iloilo Strait]] from Jordan is [[Iloilo City]] on the island of [[Panay]].\n\n==Barangays==\n\nJordan is subdivided into 14 [[barangay]]s.{{PSGC detail|area}}\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* Alaguisoc\n* Balcon Maravilla\n* Balcon Melliza\n* Bugnay\n* Buluangan\n* Espinosa\n* Hoskyn\n* Lawi\n* Morobuan\n* [[Poblacion]]\n* Rizal\n* [[Alibhon|San Miguel]] \n* Sinapsapan\n* Santa Teresa\n}}\n\n==Climate==\n{{Weather box\n| location     = Jordan, Guimaras\n| width        = auto\n| metric first = Yes\n| single line  = Yes\n| Jan high C = 30\n| Jan low C  = 21\n| Feb high C = 31\n| Feb low C  = 21\n| Mar high C = 32\n| Mar low C  = 22\n| Apr high C = 33\n| Apr low C  = 23\n| May high C = 32\n| May low C  = 24\n| Jun high C = 30\n| Jun low C  = 24\n| Jul high C = 29\n| Jul low C  = 24\n| Aug high C = 29\n| Aug low C  = 24\n| Sep high C = 28\n| Sep low C  = 24\n| Oct high C = 29\n| Oct low C  = 24\n| Nov high C = 30\n| Nov low C  = 23\n| Dec high C = 30\n| Dec low C  = 22\n| Jan precipitation mm = 19\n| Feb precipitation mm = 17\n| Mar precipitation mm = 26\n| Apr precipitation mm = 37\n| May precipitation mm = 119\n| Jun precipitation mm = 191\n| Jul precipitation mm = 258\n| Aug precipitation mm = 260\n| Sep precipitation mm = 248\n| Oct precipitation mm = 196\n| Nov precipitation mm = 97\n| Dec precipitation mm = 39\n| Jan rain days        = 7.2\n| Feb rain days        = 5.2\n| Mar rain days        = 8.3\n| Apr rain days        = 11.9\n| May rain days        = 22.3\n| Jun rain days        = 26.5\n| Jul rain days        = 28.3\n| Aug rain days        = 28.2\n| Sep rain days        = 27.3\n| Oct rain days        = 26.4\n| Nov rain days        = 18.7\n| Dec rain days        = 11.8\n| source 1 = Meteoblue <ref name=\"met_norms\">\n{{cite web \n| url = https://www.meteoblue.com/en/weather/historyclimate/climatemodelled/jordan_philippines_1710116\n| title =  Jordan: Average Temperatures and Rainfall\n| publisher = Meteoblue\n| accessdate = 28 April 2020 }}</ref>\n| date = 28 April 2020  \n}}\n\n==History==\nThe name of the town used to be Nagaba but was changed in 1902 to Jordan.<ref name=Act433>{{cite web|title=Act No. 433, AN ACT changing the name of the municipality of Nagaba, in the Province of Iloilo, to that of Jordan|url=http://philippinelaw.info/statutes/act433.html|publisher=PhilippineLaw.info|accessdate=12 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130319220127/http://philippinelaw.info/statutes/act433.html|archive-date=19 March 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The name ''Jord\u00e1n'', the [[Spanish language in the Philippines|Spanish]] name for the [[Jordan River]], was chosen by the residents in honor of [[John the Baptist]], their [[patron saint]].<ref name=Jordan/> According to local folklore, he saved the inhabitants from slaughter during the Moro raid in the Spanish era.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\nIn 1918, the municipality was formed when it separated from [[Buenavista, Guimaras|Buenavista]], with Valeriano Villanueva as the first appointed ''Presidente Municipal''. After elections in 1919, Hugo Ch\u00e1vez became the next mayor, followed by Licerio Segovia (1921-1923), Alberto Gonzaga (1923-1925), Feliz Ronzales (1925-1928), Hilario Nava (1929-1932), again Hugo Ch\u00e1vez (1932-1938), and Leodegario Galarpe (1939-1941).<ref name=Jordan/>\n\n[[Nueva Valencia, Guimaras|Nueva Valencia]] was established as a separate municipality in 1941. In July 1995 [[San Lorenzo, Guimaras|San Lorenzo]] and [[Sibunag, Guimaras|Sibunag]] were created, leaving Jordan with only 14 barangays. Before these two towns was created, Jordan was composed of 33 barangays.\n\n==Demographics==\n\n{{Philippine Census \n| align= none\n| title= Population census of Jordan\n| 1903 = 7475\n| 1918 = 15323\n| 1939 = 23053\n| 1948 = 15677\n| 1960 = 20575\n| 1970 = 27016\n| 1975 = 32474\n| 1980 = 36014\n| 1990 = 45852\t\n| 1995 = 25321\n| 2000 = 28745\n| 2007 = 32524\n| 2010 = 34791\n| 2015 = 36096\n| 2020 =\n| 2025 =\n| 2030 =\n| footnote= Source: [[Philippine Statistics Authority]]{{PH census|2015}}{{PH census|2010}}{{PH census|2007}}{{LWUA population data}} \n}}\n\n\nIn the {{PH wikidata|population_as_of}}, the population of Jordan, Guimaras, was {{PH wikidata|population_total}} people,{{PH census|current}} with a density of {{convert|{{sigfig|{{PH wikidata|population_total}}/{{PH wikidata|area}}|2}}|PD/km2|disp=or}}.\n\nIn the 2000 census, in an area of 126&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>., it had a population of 28,745 people in 5,397 households, and in 2007, 32,525 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://guimaras.gov.ph/quickfacts/|title=Guimaras Quick Facts|publisher=Guimaras.gov.ph|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415103046/http://guimaras.gov.ph/quickfacts/|archivedate=2012-04-15 }}</ref> In the 2010 census, its population had increased to 34,791 persons.\n\n==Notable people==\n*Chrisanta Seboc - Child hero who saved two of her younger siblings from a fire at home in July 1996.<ref>{{cite news|last=Defeo|first=Ruben|title=https://www.philstar.com/lifestyle/arts-and-culture/2003/07/28/215269/why-lorenza-agoncillo146s-portrait-hanging-museo-pambata|url=https://www.philstar.com/lifestyle/arts-and-culture/2003/07/28/215269/why-lorenza-agoncillo146s-portrait-hanging-museo-pambata|accessdate=7 February 2020|work=[[The Philippine Star|Philstar.com]]|publisher=Philstar Global Corp.|date=July 28, 2003}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120413163013/http://nap.psa.gov.ph/activestats/psgc/default.asp Philippine Standard Geographic Code]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20131004104825/http://census.gov.ph/ Philippine Census Information]\n\n{{Geographic location\n| Centre    = Jordan\n| North     = [[Iloilo City]]<br>''[[Iloilo Strait]]''\n| Northeast = [[Buenavista, Guimaras|Buenavista]]\n| East   